<subSubSection id="C30108F90AF6468B2CACFDAAFB50D5B3" pageId="217" pageNumber="218" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA45B720AF6468B2CACFDAAFB50D5B3" blockId="217.[151,1437,153,756]" pageId="217" pageNumber="218">
<emphasis id="B96F87600AF6468B2CACFDAAFE8FD578" bold="true" box="[199,324,548,575]" pageId="217" pageNumber="218">Comment.</emphasis>
<collectingRegion id="49DF95900AF6468B2D26FDABFEBCD578" box="[333,375,549,575]" country="Cameroon" name="North" pageId="217" pageNumber="218">Not</collectingRegion>
only are the hosts of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B20F10AF6468B2E1BFDABFD20D578" box="[624,747,549,575]" pageId="217" pageNumber="218">Aclerdinae</taxonomicName>
(bar perhaps 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B20F10AF6468B2FE2FDABFBEBD578" authorityName="Howell. Macropterous" authorityYear="1972" box="[905,1056,549,575]" class="Insecta" family="Aclerdidae" genus="Aclerda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="217" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tillandsiae">
<emphasis id="B96F87600AF6468B2FE2FDABFBEBD578" box="[905,1056,549,575]" italics="true" pageId="217" pageNumber="218">A. tillandsiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and Rhodesaclerdinae quite different but, despite their still clearly belonging to the 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B20F10AF6468B2E92FDC7FCBCD524" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1905" box="[761,887,585,611]" class="Insecta" family="Aclerdidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="217" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Aclerdidae</taxonomicName>
, the adult males of these two subfamilies differ quite significantly morphologically. Specifically, those of Rhodesaclerdinae have (character-states on 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B20F10AF6468B296EFDE3FA4BD5C0" box="[1285,1408,621,647]" pageId="217" pageNumber="218">Aclerdinae</taxonomicName>
in brackets): (i) a strong sclerotised ridge around each ocellus (absent); (ii) antennae with 7 or 8 segments (10); (iii) frequent fs on margins and venter of abdomen (fs absent on abdomen); and (iv) claws with a denticle (absent). As an example of Rhodesaclerdinae, 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B20F10AF6468B2E79FD54FCA8D5B4" authority="Hodgson &amp; Millar" authorityName="Hodgson &amp; Millar. Macropterous" authorityYear="2002" box="[530,867,729,755]" class="Insecta" family="Aclerdidae" genus="Rhodesaclerda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="217" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insleyae">
<emphasis id="B96F87600AF6468B2E79FD54FD46D5B4" box="[530,653,729,755]" italics="true" pageId="217" pageNumber="218">R. insleyae</emphasis>
Hodgson &amp; Millar
</taxonomicName>
is illustrated here (
<figureCitation id="132047F70AF6468B2851FD57FB45D5B3" box="[1082,1166,729,756]" captionStart="FIGURE 86" captionStartId="219.[151,250,1846,1871]" captionTargetBox="[160,1423,191,1821]" captionTargetId="figure@219.[151,1436,181,1821]" captionTargetPageId="219" captionText="FIGURE 86. Rhodesaclerda insleyae Hodgson &amp; Millar. Macropterous male. (Aclerdidae, Rhodesaclerdinae).Where D=simple pore and R=dermal reticulations on ocular sclerite." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3774350" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3774350/files/figure.png" pageId="217" pageNumber="218">Fig. 86</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
